for research on oral poetics, such as construction grammar or conversation analysis. The key for connecting the two disciplines is their common focus on usage and performance. This collection of papers explores how some of the latest research on language and cognition can contribute to advances in oral studies. At the same time, it shows how research on verbal art in its natural, oral medium can lead to new insights in semantics, pragmatics, or multimodal communication. The ultimate goal is to pave the way towards a Cognitive Oral Poetics, a new interdisciplinary field for the study or oral poetry as a window to the mind.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCognitive grammar. 0aFolk poetryxHistory and criticism. 0aOral-formulaic analysis. 0aPoetics. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aOral formulaic style.  aconversation analysis.  aframes and constructions.  amultimodality and narrative structuring.1 aAntovic, Mihailo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAntović, Mihailo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoas, Hans C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonifazi, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCánovas, Cristóbal Pagán, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuffy, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKreij, Mark de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMinchin, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPagán Cánovas, Cristóbal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPerson, Raymond F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShort, William Michael, eco